points.name: Nechung
points.description:
Nechung Monastery, Nechung Gompa, is the seat of the State Oracle of Tibet. It is also referred to as Sungi Gyelpoi Tsenkar, the "Demon Fortress of the Oracle King."

points.name: Samye
points.description:
The Samye Monastery or Samye Gompa is the first Buddhist monastery built in Tibet. It was probably first constructed between 775-9 CE under the patronage of King Trisong Detsen of Tibet who sought to revitalize Buddhism, which had declined since its introduction by King Songtsän Gampo in the 7th century. The monastery is in Dranang, Lhoka Prefecture. It was supposedly modeled on the design of Odantapuri in what is now Bihar, India.
Wikipedia:Samye
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Sera Monastery
points.description:
Sera Monastery is one of the "great three" Gelug university monasteries of Tibet, located 2.01 km north of Lhasa and about 5 km north of the Jokhang. The other two are Ganden Monastery and Drepung Monastery. The origin of its name is attributed to a fact that the site where the monastery was built was surrounded by wild roses in bloom.
Wikipedia:Sera Monastery
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Jokhang
points.description:
The Jokhang is a Buddhist temple in Barkhor Square in Lhasa, the capital city of Tibet. Tibetans, in general, consider this temple as the most sacred and important temple in Tibet. The temple is currently maintained by the Gelug school, but they accept worshipers from all sects of Buddhism. The temple's architectural style is a mixture of Indian vihara design, Tibetan and Nepalese design.
Wikipedia:Jokhang
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Drepung Monastery
points.description:
Drepung Monastery located at the foot of Mount Gephel, is one of the "great three" Gelukpa university monasteries of Tibet. The other two are Ganden and Sera. Drepung is the largest of all Tibetan monasteries and is located on the Gambo Utse mountain, five kilometers from the western suburb of Lhasa.
Wikipedia:Drepung Monastery
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Arkaim
points.description:
Arkaim is an archaeological site situated in the Southern Urals steppe, 8.2 kilometres (5.1 mi) north-to-northwest of the village of Amurskiy and 2.3 km (1.4 mi) south-to-southeast of the village of Alexandrovskiy, in the Chelyabinsk Oblast, Russia, just to the north from the Kazakhstan border. The site is generally dated to the 17th century BC. Earlier dates, up to the 20th century BC, have been proposed. It was a settlement of the Sintashta-Petrovka culture.
Wikipedia:Arkaim
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Russia

People that enter the forest say that this clearing is the hotspot for the otherworldly feelings you get in Hoia Baciu. Some have linked it to the reported UFO spottings.

points.name: Volcán de Colima
points.description:
The Volcán de Colima, also known as Volcán de Fuego, is part of the Colima Volcanic Complex (CVC) consisting of Volcán de Colima, Nevado de Colima and the eroded El Cantaro (listed as extinct). It is the youngest of the three and as of 2015 is one of the most active volcanos in Mexico and in North America. It has erupted more than 40 times since 1576. One of the largest eruptions was on January 20–24, 1913. Nevado de Colima, also known as Tzapotépetl, lies 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) north of its more active neighbor and is the taller of the two at 4,271+ meters (14,015+ ft). It is the 26th-most prominent peak in North America.
Wikipedia:Volcán de Colima
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Mexico

points.name: Potala Palace
points.description:
The Potala Palace in Lhasa, Tibet Autonomous Region was the chief residence of the Dalai Lama until the 14th Dalai Lama fled to India during the 1959 Tibetan uprising. It is now a museum and World Heritage Site. The palace is named after Mount Potalaka, the mythical abode of the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara. The 5th Dalai Lama started its construction in 1645 after one of his spiritual advisers, Konchog Chophel (died 1646), pointed out that the site was ideal as a seat of government, situated as it is between Drepung and Sera monasteries and the old city of Lhasa. It may overlay the remains of an earlier fortress called the White or Red Palace on the site, built by Songtsän Gampo in 637.
Wikipedia:Potala Palace
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Dancing Wood
points.description:
Phenomenon of Dancing wood. This is indeed a unique place in Kaliningrad region, Russia, in the national park Curonian, it is called “Dancing woods.” To understand the phenomenon of twisted trees anomaly, many scientists have tried different hypothesis: environmental factors, genetic factors, exposure to viruses or pests, and even a special cosmic energy of the place. The place is far from being normal, if you come in to a few meters, you feel something is wrong, as if it’s the world of spirits, the place has a strong energy. The staff of the national park do not believe in supernatural, they see the answer in the geomagnetic field. A similar place called “Troll Forest” is in Denmark, and it is also on the Baltic coast. No one has fully explained the nature of this phenomenon.
Wikipedia:Dancing Wood
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Links:http://viola.bz/phenomenon-of-dancing-wood/
Country:Russia

points.name: Haʻamonga ʻa Maui
points.description:
Haʻamonga ʻa Maui ("The Burden of Maui") is a stone trilithon located in Tonga, on the eastern part of the island of Tongatapu. It was built in the 13th century by King Tuʻitātui in honor of his two sons. The monument is sometimes called the "Stonehenge of the Pacific".
Wikipedia:Haʻamonga ʻa Maui
